tyrosine to L-DOPA","Hydroxylation of dopamine","Methylation of noradrenaline","Oxidation of dopamine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe synthesis of adrenaline occurs through multiple enzymatic steps. The final step involves \u003Cstrong\u003Emethylation of noradrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E by the enzyme phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase (PNMT), which adds a methyl group to noradrenaline to form adrenaline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other steps in catecholamine synthesis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecarboxylation of L-DOPA\u003C/strong\u003E occurs early in the pathway and forms dopamine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA\u003C/strong\u003E is the first step in the pathway and is catalysed by tyrosine hydroxylase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxylation of dopamine\u003C/strong\u003E forms noradrenaline and occurs before the final methylation step\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxidation of dopamine\u003C/strong\u003E is not a step in adrenaline synthesis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis synthesis pathway occurs primarily in the adrenal medulla, where PNMT is highly expressed. The presence of high cortisol concentrations from the adjacent adrenal cortex induces PNMT expression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adrenaline is synthesised from tyrosine through a pathway involving L-DOPA and noradrenaline.","The final step in adrenaline synthesis involves methylation of noradrenaline by phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase.","Adrenaline synthesis occurs primarily in the adrenal medulla where high local cortisol concentrations induce PNMT expression."],"references":["Blocks testosterone synthesis - This describes the mechanism ofTherapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:44:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:46:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9451"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76230"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i